Dirt

This is the track profile for all 8.5 furlong dirt races at Gulfstream Park, there are 171 races in the dataset, contested by 1349 runners. The oldest race in the dataset was run on 2012-12-01 while the most recent was run on 2014-12-13.

Summary

A few quick and dirty summary plots highlighting the different race types and field sizes. CLM races are the most common over the 8.5 furlong course, with 51 races. The average field size for 8.5 furlong races is 7.89.

Draw

The 8.5 furlong course is run round two turns, the first turn starts soon after horses jump from the starting gates, and continues for roughly 2 furlongs, the second turn ends roughly 2f from the finish line. Counting winners is the typical way to assess any draw bias, but winners ignore a large number of runners, and if there was any such bias, it should be seen across all runners, so percentage of runners beaten is to be used (gates must have a minimum of 5 runs):

A fair draw would expect to see each draw beat 50% of their rivals, runners draw in gate 1 beat more than 55% of their rivals.

The draw will likely have an impact on the distance horses travel, especially as the first turn is such a short distance from the start. Horses drawn wide (high) will likely be forced wide. Unsurprisingly, horses drawn in gate 1 travel the least distance, with an average trip of 5677.93 feet, while horses draw in gate 10 travel an average distance of 5716.79, a difference of 38.86 feet (gates must have a minimum of 5 runs used). The plot below shows boxplots of distance raced by horses in each starting gate.

Race Shape

Race shape on dirt is quite consistent even across a variety of distances, as the surface rarely allows horses who started slowly to finish faster (you will see the difference in affect looking at 8f turf race shape). The plot below shows the sectional speeds of winners, to be clear these arent cumulative speeds, but the speed from one sectional to the next (taking into account the distance travelled - Trakus data - for each horse), so from the start to 2f, from 2f to 3f, etc. Winners are slowing at the finish, but as significantly as seen in dirt sprints, but still slowing.

The fastest opening half mile by a horse who went on to win was by ORB on 23/02/13 in race 11, recording a speed of 59.57 feet per second. There were horses who ran faster, CERRO ran the opening 4f in a speed of 59.67 ft per second. Both horses were competing in the same STK race, potentially benefitting from a runup of 60 feet.

Pace

Finishing Speeds also reflect the slowing nature of dirt.

## 6.5f FinSpd 4.5f FinSpd 2.5f FinSpd 1.5f FinSpd   1f FinSpd 0.5f FinSpd 
##      0.9939      0.9767      0.9531      0.9394      0.9314      0.9124

The plots below show the distribution of 4.5f Finishing Speeds for winners compared to The Rest, and the opening 4f sectionals for winners compared to The Rest. The distributions are similar, especially the opening 4f where winners dont really differentiate themselves to The Rest as we saw in dirt sprints. Winners, on average, run the opening 4f in 48.2, compared to The Rest, who run the opening 4f in 48.54, a difference of 0.34 seconds. For reference, the horses leading their race after 4f run the opening 4f in an average time of 47.88. It is the ability to carry that early speed to the finish that sees winners separate themselves from The Rest.

Plotting the opening 4f sectional against the closing 4f Finishing Speeds the difference becomes a little more clear. Unlike dirt sprints where Winners were seen to be running faster early, over 8.5 furlong races, horses over 8.5 furlongs have time to make up ground on tiring rivals more easily that they may have lost early .

The winner with the highest 4.5f Finishing Speed was EVIL POWDER when winning a st op clm (race 2 on 16/01/13), after an opening 4f of 50.98 EVIL POWDER recorded a Finishing Speed of 1.016. The winner with the fastest opening 4f was WILDCAT RED when winning a stk (race 9 on 28/06/14), recording a time of 45.91 over the opening half mile and a 4.5f Finishing Speed of 0.957.

Turf

This is the track profile for all 8.5 furlong turf races at Gulfstream Park, there are 506 races in the dataset, contested by 4865 runners. The oldest race in the dataset was run on 2012-12-01 while the most recent was run on 2014-12-14.

Summary

A few quick and dirty summary plots highlighting the different race types and field sizes. CLM races are the most common over the 8.5 furlong course, with 188 races. The average field size for 8.5 furlong races is 9.61.

Draw

The 8.5 furlong course is run round two turns, the first turn starts soon after horses jump from the starting gates, and continues for roughly 2 furlongs, the second turn ends roughly 2f from the finish line. Counting winners is the typical way to assess any draw bias, but winners ignore a large number of runners, and if there was any such bias, it should be seen across all runners, so percentage of runners beaten is to be used (gates must have a minimum of 5 runs):

A fair draw would expect to see each draw beat 50% of their rivals, runners draw in gate 1 beat more than 55% of their rivals.

The draw will likely have an impact on the distance horses travel, especially as the first turn is such a short distance from the start. Horses drawn wide (high) will likely be forced wide. Unsurprisingly, horses drawn in gate 1 travel the least distance, with an average trip of 5679.89 feet, while horses draw in gate 14 travel an average distance of 5710, a difference of 30.11 feet (gates must have a minimum of 5 runs used). The plot below shows boxplots of distance raced by horses in each starting gate (the large-ish number of outliers for each gate are likely due to rail adjustments).

Race Shape

Race shape on turf courses isnt quite as predictable as on dirt courses, as the surface allows horses who started slowly to finish faster. The plot below shows the sectional speeds of winners, to be clear these arent cumulative speeds, but the speed from one sectional to the next (taking into account the distance travelled - Trakus data - for each horse), so from the start to 2f, from 2f to 3f, etc. Winners are still typically running slower over the final 0.5f but the fall off isnt as sharp as seen on dirt, and the middle part of the race from 2f to ~7.5f sees runners showing consistent speed.

The fastest opening half mile by a horse who went on to win was by KEY TO POWER on 26/02/14 in race 10, recording a speed of 59.66 feet per second. There were horses who ran faster, HARD ENOUGH ran the opening 4f in a speed of 61.37 ft per second.

Pace

Finishing Speeds also reflect the consistent speed throughout the race, par Finishing Speeds for winners are:

## 6.5f FinSpd 4.5f FinSpd 2.5f FinSpd 1.5f FinSpd   1f FinSpd 0.5f FinSpd 
##      1.0058      1.0062      1.0033      0.9996      0.9965      0.9842

The plots below show the distribution of 4.5f Finishing Speeds for winners compared to The Rest, and the opening 4f sectionals for winners compared to The Rest. The distributions for the opening 4f are very similar, Winners, on average, run the opening 4f in 48.89, compared to The Rest, who run the opening 4f in 49.08, a difference of 0.19 seconds. For reference, the horses leading their race after 4f run the opening 4f in an average time of 48.38. The 4f Finishing Speeds are also very similar.

Plotting the opening 4f sectional against the closing 4.5f Finishing Speeds the difference becomes a little more clear. Runners arent necessarily punished if they start slowly as in sprint, or dirt, races, the kinder surface means horses are capable of finishing much faster and making up ground on horses who started faster.

The winner with the highest 4.5f Finishing Speed was GREENGRASSOFYOMING when winning a st all (race 8 on 28/02/14), after an opening 4f of 51.49 GREENGRASSOFYOMING recorded a Finishing Speed of 1.06. The winner with the fastest opening half mile was DEANAALLENSKITTEN when winning a st all (race 6 on 24/03/13), recording a time of 45.68 over the opening half mile and a 4.5f Finishing Speed of 0.982.
